check.packages_bioconductor <- function(pkg){
    new.pkg <- pkg[!(pkg %in%library()[]$result[,1])]
    source("https://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
    if (length(new.pkg)) 
        biocLite(new.pkg, dependencies = TRUE)
    sapply(pkg, library, character.only = TRUE)
}

Gene Ontology

In large scale analyses genes and/or proteins are used as statistical objects. This approach can be enriched with existing knowledge for each gene-protein in order to obtain more insightful and biologicaly relevant results. This is a way of combining knowledge from single gene/protein genetic and biochemical research with the holistic approach of big data.

What are ontologies

As a tool

Gene ontology annotation in r

Bioconductor has packages in R that do Gene Ontology annotation in genes of many organisms with different types of database IDs. For detailed tutorials look (Sinha 2014).

# data from Biogrid
Escherichia_coli_biogrid <- read.delim(file = "Data/BIOGRID-ORGANISM-Escherichia_coli_K12_MG1655-3.5.166.mitab.txt",sep = "\t",header = T) %>% mutate(InteractorA_entrez=gsub("(.*):(.*)","\\2",X.ID.Interactor.A), InteractorB_entrez=gsub("(.*):(.*)","\\2",ID.Interactor.B))

Escherichia_coli_biogrid_proteins <- as.character(unique(c(Escherichia_coli_biogrid$InteractorA_entrez,Escherichia_coli_biogrid$InteractorB_entrez))) # gene universe

Escherichia_coli_biogrid_physical_association <- Escherichia_coli_biogrid %>% filter(Interaction.Types %in% c("psi-mi:MI:0407(direct interaction)","psi-mi:MI:0915(physical association)"))

Escherichia_coli_biogrid_physical_association_proteins <- as.character(unique(c(Escherichia_coli_biogrid_physical_association$InteractorA_entrez,Escherichia_coli_biogrid_physical_association$InteractorB_entrez))) # genes of interest

Singular enrichment analysis

In order to examine which gene ontology terms are overrepresented in the genes of our network we have to do a statistic test. Most commonly used tests is the Fishers exact test, the chi square test and the binomial test. We will use the Fisher s exact test for the Biological Process component of Gene Ontology.

####################################### Plot GO graph #########################################

showSigOfNodes <- showSigOfNodes(sampleGOdata, score(resultFisher), firstSigNodes = 53, useInfo = 'all')

# it induces the GO graph with the quered IDs. 
showSigOfNodes
## $dag
## A graphNEL graph with directed edges
## Number of Nodes = 75 
## Number of Edges = 151 
## 
## $complete.dag
## [1] "A graph with 75 nodes."
printGraph(sampleGOdata, resultFisher, firstSigNodes = 10, useInfo = 'all',fn.prefix = "Gene Ontology enriched terms", pdfSW = TRUE)
## Gene Ontology enriched terms_classic_10_all  --- no of nodes:  26
showSigOfNodes_igraph <- graph_from_graphnel(showSigOfNodes$dag, name = TRUE, weight = TRUE,
  unlist.attrs = TRUE)

summary(showSigOfNodes_igraph)
## IGRAPH d93963a DNW- 75 151 -- 
## + attr: name (v/c), weight (e/n)

All these test share the same assumption for the null hypothesis, that the probabilities for the selection of each gene are equal (Rivals et al. 2007). But it turns out that thay are not because the structure of gene ontology bipartite network of genes and gene terms has a heavy tail distribution and hence these tests are biased to high degree terms (Glass and Girvan 2014).

Nice explanation to the biases of gene ontology

Kegg pathway annotation

library(KEGGgraph)
library(KEGG.db)
library(org.Dm.eg.db)
library(KEGGREST)


proteins_cluster <- intresting_genes_Essential
myEID <- unlist(mget(proteins_cluster, org.Dm.egFLYBASE2EG, ifnotfound=NA))
myEID <- as.character(myEID)

kegg <- as.data.frame(unlist(mget(as.character(myEID), org.Dm.egPATH,
       ifnotfound=list(NA))),row.names = NULL) %>% tibble::rownames_to_column(.,var="Var1")
colnames(kegg) <- c("entrez_id", "kegg_pathway_id")

kegg_summary <- kegg %>% group_by(kegg_pathway_id) %>% summarize(proteins=n()) %>% ungroup()

kegg_summary[1,3] <- keggGet("dme00190")[[1]]$NAME
kegg_summary[2,3] <- keggGet("dme01100")[[1]]$NAME
kegg_summary[3,3] <- keggGet("dme03010")[[1]]$NAME
kegg_summary[4,3] <- keggGet("dme03050")[[1]]$NAME

colnames(kegg_summary) <- c("kegg pathway id", "proteins", "kegg pathway name")

write.table(x = kegg_summary, file = "../Thesis_Essentiality_Drosophila_Signed_Network/Tables/Essential_cluster_kegg_summary.csv", sep = ",", col.names = TRUE,row.names = FALSE)

library(pathview)

pv.out_1 <- pathview(gene.data = kegg$entrez_id, pathway.id = as.character(kegg_summary$kegg_pathway_id[1]), species = "dme", out.suffix = "dros_essential_cluster", kegg.native = F)
